1
00:00:01,820 --> 00:00:05,085
The learning algorithm
that we developed,

2
00:00:05,085 --> 00:00:07,245
even while you're
still learning how

3
00:00:07,245 --> 00:00:09,870
to approximate Q(s,a),

4
00:00:09,870 --> 00:00:13,695
you need to take some
actions in the lunar lander.

5
00:00:13,695 --> 00:00:15,465
How do you pick those actions

6
00:00:15,465 --> 00:00:16,755
while you're still learning?

7
00:00:16,755 --> 00:00:19,170
The most common way
to do so is to use

8
00:00:19,170 --> 00:00:21,900
something called an
Epsilon-greedy policy.

9
00:00:21,900 --> 00:00:24,030
Let's take a look
at how that works.

10
00:00:24,030 --> 00:00:27,270
Here's the algorithm
that you saw earlier.

11
00:00:27,270 --> 00:00:29,805
One of the steps in
the algorithm is

12
00:00:29,805 --> 00:00:33,300
to take actions in
the lunar lander.

13
00:00:33,300 --> 00:00:36,225
When the learning algorithm
is still running,

14
00:00:36,225 --> 00:00:37,890
we don't really know what's

15
00:00:37,890 --> 00:00:39,810
the best action to
take in every state.

16
00:00:39,810 --> 00:00:42,225
If we did, we'd already
be done learning.

17
00:00:42,225 --> 00:00:44,930
But even while we're still
learning and don't have

18
00:00:44,930 --> 00:00:48,020
a very good estimate
of Q(s,a) yet,

19
00:00:48,020 --> 00:00:49,955
how do we take actions

20
00:00:49,955 --> 00:00:52,280
in this step of the
learning algorithm?

21
00:00:52,280 --> 00:00:54,150
Let's look at some options.

22
00:00:54,150 --> 00:00:56,405
When you're in some state s,

23
00:00:56,405 --> 00:00:59,720
we might not want to take
actions totally at random

24
00:00:59,720 --> 00:01:03,740
because that will
often be a bad action.

25
00:01:03,740 --> 00:01:09,320
One natural option would be
to pick whenever in state s,

26
00:01:09,320 --> 00:01:13,705
pick an action a that
maximizes Q(s,a).

27
00:01:13,705 --> 00:01:16,700
We may say, even
if Q(s,a) is not

28
00:01:16,700 --> 00:01:19,430
a great estimate
of the Q function,

29
00:01:19,430 --> 00:01:22,805
let's just do our best
and use our current guess

30
00:01:22,805 --> 00:01:26,885
of Q(s,a) and pick the
action a that maximizes it.

31
00:01:26,885 --> 00:01:29,990
It turns out this may work okay,

32
00:01:29,990 --> 00:01:32,705
but isn't the best option.

33
00:01:32,705 --> 00:01:36,025
Instead, here's what
is commonly done.

34
00:01:36,025 --> 00:01:37,420
Here's option 2,

35
00:01:37,420 --> 00:01:39,305
which is most of the time,

36
00:01:39,305 --> 00:01:42,305
let's say with
probability of 0.95,

37
00:01:42,305 --> 00:01:47,335
pick the action that
maximizes Q(s,a).

38
00:01:47,335 --> 00:01:49,610
Most of the time we try to pick

39
00:01:49,610 --> 00:01:52,670
a good action using our
current guess of Q(s,a).

40
00:01:52,670 --> 00:01:55,340
But the small fraction
of the time, let's say,

41
00:01:55,340 --> 00:01:56,960
five percent of the time,

42
00:01:56,960 --> 00:01:59,390
we'll pick an action a randomly.

43
00:01:59,390 --> 00:02:02,675
Why do we want to occasionally
pick an action randomly?

44
00:02:02,675 --> 00:02:05,190
Well, here's why.
Suppose there's

45
00:02:05,190 --> 00:02:08,880
some strange reason that
Q(s,a) was initialized

46
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:11,970
randomly so that the
learning algorithm thinks

47
00:02:11,970 --> 00:02:15,570
that firing the main thruster
is never a good idea.

48
00:02:15,570 --> 00:02:18,395
Maybe the neural
network parameters

49
00:02:18,395 --> 00:02:20,805
were initialized so that Q(s,

50
00:02:20,805 --> 00:02:25,130
main) is always very low.

51
00:02:25,130 --> 00:02:26,615
If that's the case,

52
00:02:26,615 --> 00:02:28,340
then the neural network,

53
00:02:28,340 --> 00:02:29,990
because it's trying
to pick the action

54
00:02:29,990 --> 00:02:31,970
a that maximizes Q(s,a),

55
00:02:31,970 --> 00:02:35,450
it will never ever try
firing the main thruster.

56
00:02:35,450 --> 00:02:39,125
Because it never ever tries
firing the main thruster,

57
00:02:39,125 --> 00:02:41,030
it will never learn that firing

58
00:02:41,030 --> 00:02:44,245
the main thruster is actually
sometimes a good idea.

59
00:02:44,245 --> 00:02:47,525
Because of the random
initialization,

60
00:02:47,525 --> 00:02:50,930
if the neural network somehow
initially gets stuck in

61
00:02:50,930 --> 00:02:52,100
this mind that some things are

62
00:02:52,100 --> 00:02:54,650
bad idea, just by chance,

63
00:02:54,650 --> 00:02:56,690
then option 1,

64
00:02:56,690 --> 00:02:59,810
it means that it will never
try out those actions and

65
00:02:59,810 --> 00:03:01,610
discover that maybe is

66
00:03:01,610 --> 00:03:04,055
actually a good idea
to take that action,

67
00:03:04,055 --> 00:03:06,430
like fire the main
thrusters sometimes.

68
00:03:06,430 --> 00:03:08,765
Under option 2 on every step,

69
00:03:08,765 --> 00:03:11,990
we have some small
probability of trying out

70
00:03:11,990 --> 00:03:15,320
different actions so that
the neural network can

71
00:03:15,320 --> 00:03:20,120
learn to overcome its own
possible preconceptions

72
00:03:20,120 --> 00:03:21,440
about what might be

73
00:03:21,440 --> 00:03:24,440
a bad idea that turns
out not to be the case.

74
00:03:24,440 --> 00:03:27,770
This idea of picking
actions randomly is

75
00:03:27,770 --> 00:03:31,150
sometimes called an
exploration step.

76
00:03:31,150 --> 00:03:33,620
Because we're going to try

77
00:03:33,620 --> 00:03:35,795
out something that may
not be the best idea,

78
00:03:35,795 --> 00:03:37,190
but we're going to just try out

79
00:03:37,190 --> 00:03:39,065
some action in some
circumstances,

80
00:03:39,065 --> 00:03:41,870
explore and learn more
about an action in

81
00:03:41,870 --> 00:03:43,580
the circumstance
where we may not have

82
00:03:43,580 --> 00:03:45,730
had as much experience before.

83
00:03:45,730 --> 00:03:49,105
Taking an action that
maximizes Q(s,a),

84
00:03:49,105 --> 00:03:54,680
sometimes this is called a
greedy action because we're

85
00:03:54,680 --> 00:04:00,155
trying to actually maximize
our return by picking this.

86
00:04:00,155 --> 00:04:02,630
Or in the reinforcement
learning literature,

87
00:04:02,630 --> 00:04:07,845
sometimes you'll also hear
this as an exploitation step.

88
00:04:07,845 --> 00:04:10,490
I know that exploitation
is not a good thing,

89
00:04:10,490 --> 00:04:13,160
nobody should ever
explore anyone else.

90
00:04:13,160 --> 00:04:15,380
But historically, this
was the term used

91
00:04:15,380 --> 00:04:17,360
in reinforcement
learning to say,

92
00:04:17,360 --> 00:04:18,800
let's exploit everything we've

93
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:20,735
learned to do the best we can.

94
00:04:20,735 --> 00:04:22,880
In the reinforcement
learning literature,

95
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:25,040
sometimes you hear
people talk about

96
00:04:25,040 --> 00:04:28,265
the exploration versus
exploitation trade-off,

97
00:04:28,265 --> 00:04:30,290
which refers to how often do

98
00:04:30,290 --> 00:04:32,270
you take actions
randomly or take

99
00:04:32,270 --> 00:04:36,260
actions that may not be the
best in order to learn more,

100
00:04:36,260 --> 00:04:40,340
versus trying to maximize
your return by say,

101
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:43,180
taking the action that
maximizes Q (s,a).

102
00:04:43,180 --> 00:04:46,780
This approach, that is
option 2, has a name,

103
00:04:46,780 --> 00:04:51,135
is called an
Epsilon-greedy policy,

104
00:04:51,135 --> 00:04:53,375
where here Epsilon is

105
00:04:53,375 --> 00:04:58,750
0.05 is the probability of
picking an action randomly.

106
00:04:58,750 --> 00:05:02,585
This is the most
common way to make

107
00:05:02,585 --> 00:05:05,285
your reinforcement
learning algorithm

108
00:05:05,285 --> 00:05:07,045
explore a little bit,

109
00:05:07,045 --> 00:05:09,400
even whilst
occasionally or maybe

110
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:11,855
most of the time
taking greedy actions.

111
00:05:11,855 --> 00:05:14,780
By the way, lot of people
have commented that

112
00:05:14,780 --> 00:05:18,080
the name Epsilon-greedy
policy is confusing because

113
00:05:18,080 --> 00:05:21,380
you're actually being greedy
95 percent of the time,

114
00:05:21,380 --> 00:05:22,985
not five percent of the time.

115
00:05:22,985 --> 00:05:26,525
So maybe 1 minus
Epsilon-greedy policy,

116
00:05:26,525 --> 00:05:28,290
because it's 95 percent greedy,

117
00:05:28,290 --> 00:05:30,470
five percent exploring, that's

118
00:05:30,470 --> 00:05:32,990
actually a more accurate
description of the algorithm.

119
00:05:32,990 --> 00:05:35,165
But for historical reasons,

120
00:05:35,165 --> 00:05:38,785
the name Epsilon-greedy
policy is what has stuck.

121
00:05:38,785 --> 00:05:41,360
This is the name that
people use to refer to

122
00:05:41,360 --> 00:05:43,835
the policy that explores

123
00:05:43,835 --> 00:05:46,520
actually Epsilon fraction
of the time rather

124
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:49,765
than this greedy Epsilon
fraction of the time.

125
00:05:49,765 --> 00:05:52,760
Lastly, one of the trick
that's sometimes used in

126
00:05:52,760 --> 00:05:56,165
reinforcement learning is
to start off Epsilon high.

127
00:05:56,165 --> 00:05:59,930
Initially, you are taking

128
00:05:59,930 --> 00:06:01,655
random actions a lot at

129
00:06:01,655 --> 00:06:04,925
a time and then
gradually decrease it,

130
00:06:04,925 --> 00:06:07,520
so that over time you are

131
00:06:07,520 --> 00:06:10,280
less likely to take
actions randomly and

132
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:11,960
more likely to use

133
00:06:11,960 --> 00:06:14,015
your improving estimates of

134
00:06:14,015 --> 00:06:16,970
the Q-function to
pick good actions.

135
00:06:16,970 --> 00:06:20,795
For example, in the
lunar lander exercise,

136
00:06:20,795 --> 00:06:23,405
you might start off with
Epsilon very, very high,

137
00:06:23,405 --> 00:06:26,120
maybe even Epsilon equals 1.0.

138
00:06:26,120 --> 00:06:27,890
You're just picking
actions completely at

139
00:06:27,890 --> 00:06:29,660
random initially and then

140
00:06:29,660 --> 00:06:34,380
gradually decrease it all
the way down to say 0.01,

141
00:06:34,380 --> 00:06:36,095
so that eventually you're

142
00:06:36,095 --> 00:06:38,600
taking greedy actions
99 percent of

143
00:06:38,600 --> 00:06:40,400
the time and acting

144
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:43,775
randomly only a very small
one percent of the time.

145
00:06:43,775 --> 00:06:46,400
If this seems complicated,
don't worry about it.

146
00:06:46,400 --> 00:06:47,705
We'll provide the code

147
00:06:47,705 --> 00:06:52,765
in the Jupiter lab that
shows you how to do this.

148
00:06:52,765 --> 00:06:54,410
If you were to implement

149
00:06:54,410 --> 00:06:56,975
the algorithm as we've
described it with

150
00:06:56,975 --> 00:06:59,720
the more efficient neural
network architecture and with

151
00:06:59,720 --> 00:07:02,765
an Epsilon-greedy
exploration policy,

152
00:07:02,765 --> 00:07:06,280
you find that they work pretty
well on the lunar lander.

153
00:07:06,280 --> 00:07:08,990
One of the things
that I've noticed for

154
00:07:08,990 --> 00:07:10,580
reinforcement
learning algorithm is

155
00:07:10,580 --> 00:07:12,965
that compared to
supervised learning,

156
00:07:12,965 --> 00:07:14,720
they're more finicky in terms

157
00:07:14,720 --> 00:07:16,910
of the choice of
hyper parameters.

158
00:07:16,910 --> 00:07:19,610
For example, in
supervised learning,

159
00:07:19,610 --> 00:07:22,910
if you set the learning rate
a little bit too small,

160
00:07:22,910 --> 00:07:25,475
then maybe the algorithm
will take longer to learn.

161
00:07:25,475 --> 00:07:27,410
Maybe it takes three
times as long to train,

162
00:07:27,410 --> 00:07:30,680
which is annoying, but
maybe not that bad.

163
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:32,870
Whereas in
reinforcement learning,

164
00:07:32,870 --> 00:07:34,905
find that if you set

165
00:07:34,905 --> 00:07:37,340
the value of Epsilon
not quite as well,

166
00:07:37,340 --> 00:07:39,620
or set other parameters
not quite as well,

167
00:07:39,620 --> 00:07:42,290
it doesn't take three
times as long to learn.

168
00:07:42,290 --> 00:07:46,070
It may take 10 times or a
100 times as long to learn.

169
00:07:46,070 --> 00:07:48,440
Reinforcement
learning algorithms,

170
00:07:48,440 --> 00:07:49,340
I think because they're are

171
00:07:49,340 --> 00:07:52,190
less mature than supervised
learning algorithms,

172
00:07:52,190 --> 00:07:53,690
are much more finicky to

173
00:07:53,690 --> 00:07:55,955
little choices of
parameters like that,

174
00:07:55,955 --> 00:08:01,040
and it actually sometimes is
frankly more frustrating to

175
00:08:01,040 --> 00:08:02,240
tune these parameters with

176
00:08:02,240 --> 00:08:04,310
reinforcement learning
algorithm compared

177
00:08:04,310 --> 00:08:06,720
to a supervised
learning algorithm.

178
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:08,840
But again, if you're
worried about

179
00:08:08,840 --> 00:08:11,315
the practice lab, the
program exercise,

180
00:08:11,315 --> 00:08:12,860
we'll give you a sense of

181
00:08:12,860 --> 00:08:15,590
good parameters to use
in the program exercise

182
00:08:15,590 --> 00:08:17,240
so that you should
be able to do that

183
00:08:17,240 --> 00:08:19,970
and successfully learn
the lunar lander,

184
00:08:19,970 --> 00:08:22,190
hopefully without
too many problems.

185
00:08:22,190 --> 00:08:24,605
In the next optional video,

186
00:08:24,605 --> 00:08:27,995
I want us to drive a couple
more algorithm refinements,

187
00:08:27,995 --> 00:08:32,045
mini batching, and also
using soft updates.

188
00:08:32,045 --> 00:08:34,475
Even without these
additional refinements,

189
00:08:34,475 --> 00:08:36,170
the algorithm will work okay,

190
00:08:36,170 --> 00:08:38,270
but these are additional
refinements that make

191
00:08:38,270 --> 00:08:40,810
the algorithm run much faster.

192
00:08:40,810 --> 00:08:43,350
It's okay if you
skip this video,

193
00:08:43,350 --> 00:08:45,080
we've provided
everything you need in

194
00:08:45,080 --> 00:08:48,080
the practice lab to hopefully
successfully complete it.

195
00:08:48,080 --> 00:08:50,390
But if you're interested
in learning about more of

196
00:08:50,390 --> 00:08:51,650
these details of two

197
00:08:51,650 --> 00:08:53,375
named reinforcement
learning algorithms,

198
00:08:53,375 --> 00:08:56,585
then come with me and let's
see in the next video,

199
00:08:56,585 --> 00:08:59,970
